nic antibiotic therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe major risk factors for hepatocellular carcinoma include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic hepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E and hepatitis C viral infections - account for approximately 80% of cases worldwide\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlcohol-related liver disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENon-alcoholic fatty liver disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHereditary haemochromatosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAflatoxin exposure from contaminated foods\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular aspirin use\u003C/strong\u003E has no established link to liver cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EProton pump inhibitor therapy\u003C/strong\u003E does not affect liver cancer risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EOral contraceptive use\u003C/strong\u003E has been associated with hepatic adenomas but not hepatocellular carcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic antibiotic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor for liver cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic viral hepatitis B and C are major risk factors for hepatocellular carcinoma","Aflatoxin exposure from contaminated food increases hepatocellular carcinoma risk","Alcohol-related liver disease and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease are significant risk factors for hepatocellular carcinoma","Hereditary haemochromatosis increases hepatocellular carcinoma risk through iron overload"],"references":["Dixon LJ, Barnes M, Tang H, Pritchard MT, Nagy LE. Kupffer cells in the liver. Compr Physiol. 2013 Apr;3(2):785-97. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c120026. PMID: 23720329; PMCID: PMC4748178","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scien